    slug: "future-tenses-will-vs-going-to",
    title: "Will vs Going To: How to Talk About the Future Correctly",
    titleAr: "Will مقابل Going To: إزاي تتكلم عن المستقبل بشكل صحيح",
    category: "Grammar",
    categoryAr: "القواعد",
    iconKey: "trendingUp", color: "#34d399",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1629470937900-f9ef0f2a8086?w=900&q=75&auto=format&fit=crop",
    preview: "English has several ways to talk about the future. Learn the real difference between 'will' and 'going to' so you never mix them up again.",
    previewAr: "اللغة الإنجليزية فيها أكتر من طريقة للتعبير عن المستقبل. تعلّم الفرق الحقيقي بين will وgoing to عشان متلخبطش بينهم تاني.",
    date: "2026-01-11",
    readTime: "6 min read",
    content: "Many learners think \"will\" and \"going to\" mean exactly the same thing. They don't. Using the wrong one can make you sound unnatural, even if your grammar is technically correct. Here's how native speakers actually choose between them.\n\n## The Core Difference\n\n**Will** is used for decisions made at the moment of speaking, predictions based on opinion, promises, and offers.\n\n**Going to** is used for plans that were already decided before now, and predictions based on evidence you can see right now.\n\n## When to Use \"Will\"\n\n**1. Instant decisions (made right now)**\n\n- The phone is ringing — I'll answer it.\n- I'm tired. I think I'll go to bed early.\n\n**2. Promises and offers**\n\n- I will help you with your homework.\n- Don't worry, I'll be there on time.\n\n**3. Predictions based on opinion or general belief**\n\n- I think it will rain tomorrow.\n- English will become even more important in the future.\n\n## When to Use \"Going To\"\n\n**1. Plans decided before the moment of speaking**\n\n- I am going to visit my parents this weekend. (already planned)\n- She is going to start a new job next month.\n\n**2. Predictions based on present evidence**\n\n- Look at those clouds — it is going to rain. (you can see the evidence now)\n- He's driving too fast. He's going to crash.\n\n## Side-by-Side Comparison\n\n- I will call you later. (decision made right now, while speaking)\n- I am going to call the client after lunch. (already planned before this conversation)\n\n- It will probably rain this weekend. (general opinion/prediction)\n- Look at that sky — it's going to rain any minute. (evidence you can see now)\n\n## The Present Continuous for Future Arrangements\n\nThere's a third common way to talk about the future: the Present Continuous, used for firm, confirmed arrangements — especially with other people.\n\n- I am meeting my manager at 3 p.m. tomorrow. (confirmed appointment)\n- We are flying to Jordan next Friday. (tickets are already booked)\n\n## Common Mistakes Arabic Speakers Make\n\n- Wrong: I will go to the dentist tomorrow, I made the appointment last week.\n- Correct: I am going to go to the dentist tomorrow. (it was already planned)\n\n- Wrong: Look at him, he will fall!\n- Correct: Look at him, he's going to fall! (visible evidence right now)\n\n## Quick Comparison Table\n\n| Will | Going To |\n|---|---|\n| Instant decision | Pre-made plan |\n| Promise / offer | Prediction from evidence |\n| Opinion-based prediction | Already decided before now |\n\n## Practice Sentences\n\n- A: \"We're out of milk.\" B: \"OK, I ___ (go) to the shop.\" \n- I ___ (start) my English course next month — I already registered.\n- Look at those dark clouds, it ___ (rain) soon.\n- I promise I ___ (call) you as soon as I land.\n\nAnswers: will go, am going to start, is going to rain, will call.\n\n## Final Tip\n\nAsk yourself: \"Did I decide this just now, or was it already planned?\" Just now → will. Already planned → going to. And if you can literally see the evidence in front of you → going to.",
    contentAr: "كتير من المتعلمين فاكرين إن \"will\" و\"going to\" معناهم نفس الحاجة بالظبط. ده مش صحيح. استخدام الصيغة الغلط ممكن يخلي كلامك غير طبيعي حتى لو القاعدة النحوية سليمة تقنياً. إليك إزاي الناطقين الأصليين فعلاً بيختاروا بينهم.\n\n## الفرق الجوهري\n\n**Will** بتُستخدم للقرارات اللي بتاخدها في لحظة الكلام نفسها، التوقعات المبنية على رأي شخصي، الوعود، والعروض.\n\n**Going to** بتُستخدم للخطط اللي كانت متقررة قبل كده، والتوقعات المبنية على دليل بتشوفه دلوقتي.\n\n## إمتى تستخدم \"Will\"\n\n**1. قرارات فورية (بتاخدها دلوقتي)**\n\n- The phone is ringing — I'll answer it.\n- I'm tired. I think I'll go to bed early.\n\n**2. وعود وعروض**\n\n- I will help you with your homework.\n- Don't worry, I'll be there on time.\n\n**3. توقعات مبنية على رأي أو اعتقاد عام**\n\n- I think it will rain tomorrow.\n- English will become even more important in the future.\n\n## إمتى تستخدم \"Going To\"\n\n**1. خطط اتقررت قبل لحظة الكلام**\n\n- I am going to visit my parents this weekend. (متخطط له بالفعل)\n- She is going to start a new job next month.\n\n**2. توقعات مبنية على دليل موجود دلوقتي**\n\n- Look at those clouds — it is going to rain. (بتشوف الدليل دلوقتي قدامك)\n- He's driving too fast. He's going to crash.\n\n## مقارنة جنب بعض\n\n- I will call you later. (قرار اتاخد دلوقتي وإنت بتتكلم)\n- I am going to call the client after lunch. (متخطط له قبل المحادثة دي)\n\n- It will probably rain this weekend. (رأي عام/توقع)\n- Look at that sky — it's going to rain any minute. (دليل بتشوفه دلوقتي)\n\n## المضارع المستمر للترتيبات المستقبلية\n\nفيه طريقة تالتة شائعة للتعبير عن المستقبل: المضارع المستمر، بيتُستخدم للترتيبات المؤكدة والمتفق عليها — خصوصاً مع ناس تانية.\n\n- I am meeting my manager at 3 p.m. tomorrow. (ميعاد مؤكد)\n- We are flying to Jordan next Friday. (التذاكر محجوزة بالفعل)\n\n## أخطاء شائعة عند الناطقين بالعربية\n\n- غلط: I will go to the dentist tomorrow, I made the appointment last week.\n- صح: I am going to go to the dentist tomorrow. (كان متخطط له بالفعل)\n\n- غلط: Look at him, he will fall!\n- صح: Look at him, he's going to fall! (دليل واضح دلوقتي)\n\n## جدول مقارنة سريع\n\n| Will | Going To |\n|---|---|\n| قرار فوري | خطة متقررة مسبقاً |\n| وعد / عرض | توقع من دليل ملموس |\n| توقع مبني على رأي | متقرر قبل لحظة الكلام |\n\n## جمل للتدريب\n\n- A: \"We're out of milk.\" B: \"OK, I ___ (go) to the shop.\" \n- I ___ (start) my English course next month — I already registered.\n- Look at those dark clouds, it ___ (rain) soon.\n- I promise I ___ (call) you as soon as I land.\n\nالإجابات: will go, am going to start, is going to rain, will call.\n\n## نصيحة أخيرة\n\nاسأل نفسك: \"أنا قررت الحاجة دي دلوقتي، ولا كانت متخطط لها قبل كده؟\" قررتها دلوقتي → will. كانت مخططة قبل كده → going to. ولو بتشوف الدليل قدامك فعلياً → going to."
